The Multi-threaded Network Port Scanner with Graphical User Interface (GUI) is a Python-based application designed to efficiently analyze network systems by identifying open, closed, and filtered ports on a target host. Ports act as communication endpoints for various network services, and identifying their status is essential for network diagnostics and security assessment.
This project utilizes socket programming to establish connection attempts with a specified range of ports on a given IP address or domain. To significantly improve scanning speed, the application implements multi-threading, allowing multiple ports to be scanned simultaneously instead of sequentially. This reduces overall scan time, especially when dealing with large port ranges.
The tool also incorporates a user-friendly GUI built using Tkinter, enabling users to easily input the target address and port range, start or stop scans, and view results in real time without requiring command-line interaction. The interface displays open ports along with their corresponding common service names (such as HTTP, FTP, SSH), helping users quickly understand which services are active on the target system.
Additionally, the scanner includes features like: Real-time result updates, Error handling for invalid inputs or unreachable hosts, Option to save scan results for further analysis
